english:
  title: Preface to the Jinsan World Manuscripts
  author: Shin Suk-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The craftsman inherits his father's trade; the physician must pass down his art through three generations. The ancients valued this deeply—was it not because mastery requires complete dedication and skill demands time's patient hand? If this holds true for lesser crafts, how much more for greater pursuits?

    In this world, countless scholars read deeply and establish their fame through letters, yet scarcely one in a thousand leaves a collected work to posterity. How rare then are those whose brilliance passes down through generations? The three Sou brothers carried forward their family's grace; the two Lu brothers linked their radiance across ages—all the world marvels at them as unprecedented. Yet they were merely father and sons, brothers joined by blood. How much rarer still are three generations in unbroken succession?

    Jiang Gong Jingchun of Jinsan came to me with a single volume, saying: "My ancestor Tongting, my father Wanyizhai, and my elder brother Renzhai each left poems and prose, yet none preserved manuscripts. I have gathered what remains in our family records and what others remember and have recorded. I humbly compile and copy these works, gathering them under the title 'Jinsan World Manuscripts,' intending to pass them to posterity. I ask you to write a preface."

    I accepted and read carefully. Tongting's work is refined and elegant; Wanyizhai's is lofty and pure; Renzhai's is plain and modest. Through three generations transmitted, each stands distinct. Yet their framework bears the same clarity, their spirit the same gravity—as if all flowed from a single hand. I have served Wanyizhai, studied alongside Renzhai from youth, and worked as colleague to Jingchun. Ever have I marveled at their household teachings, so unlike the common way. Now, reading these manuscripts, I understand at last the deep wellspring from which they flow.

    Compared to lesser crafts, their specialization and duration are indeed complete. Speaking of greater things: they may be said to have carried forward grace and linked radiance across a thousand ages, claiming beauty for all time. Alas, Renzhai departed early; Jingchun now holds the brush and is honored as master by all scholars; his sons too pursue learning with diligence. Can we say this legacy ends at merely three generations?
  footnotes:
    - Tongting, Wanyizhai (玩易齋), and Renzhai are the courtesy names or pen names of three consecutive generations of the Jiang family from Jinsan.
    - The "three Sou brothers" and "two Lu brothers" refer to famous literary families in classical Chinese tradition—the Su family (including Su Xun and his sons Su Shi and Su Zhe) and the Lu family (Lu Ji and Lu Yun), known for their poetic and scholarly achievements across generations.
    - Shin Suk-ju (1417-1475) was a celebrated Korean scholar-official of the Joseon dynasty, known for his learning and service to successive kings.
